# Windows CLI Basics

## Learning Objectives

- Use the Windows command line confidently.
- Navigate folders without clicking.
- Find files when only the file name is known.
- Read files using the terminal.
- Collect basic system and network information.

## Notes

The Windows command line allows users to interact with a Windows system by typing commands instead of using the graphical interface.

Command-line skills are useful for:

- Navigating folders
- Finding files
- Reading files
- Collecting system information
- Troubleshooting
- Security investigation tasks

## Common Windows Command Prompt Commands

| Command | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `dir` | Lists files and folders in the current directory |
| `dir /a` | Shows all items, including hidden files |
| `dir /s <file name>` | Searches all subfolders from the current directory for a file |
| `cd <folder>` | Changes to another directory |
| `cd ..` | Moves back one directory level |
| `type <file>` | Reads and displays a file in the terminal |
| `whoami` | Shows the current user |
| `ipconfig` | Shows network configuration information |

## PowerShell Companion Script

This repo includes a PowerShell script named `windows_cli_basics.ps1`.

The script demonstrates similar Windows command-line concepts using PowerShell commands, including:

- Showing the current directory
- Listing files and folders
- Displaying hidden items
- Showing the current user
- Collecting system information
- Displaying network configuration
